flowRoot.flowPara: BoniRob: an autonomous field robot platform for individual plant phenotyping
Proceedings of Joint International Agricultural Conference (2009)

Four wheel hub motors with hydraulics. Spectral imaging, 3D time-of-flight cameras, RTK-DGPS for plant phenotyping. Can change its height. Mention a Gazebo-based 3D simultated environment. Refer the the robot as a scout platform.
Have identified that robustness is a major hindrance for the introduction of a first prototype of an autonomouse agricultral field robot.
Suggest that since the devleopment of agricultural robot is complex that the application should be of comparably low complexity.
Identified crop scouting as ideal first application of autonomous platform.
Internal system communication is via ethernet, with CAN used on lower levels.

Agricultural robots - System analysis and economic feasibility
Note that fusion algorithms and data analysis, need to be adjusted to the dynamic conditions of unstructured agricultural environments.
Research into autonomous vehicles in agruculture started in the early 1960s [citation].

Goence compared autonomuos.. to conventional... and showed that when autonomouse can be utilised 23h a day they would be economocically feasible given slight reductions in navigation system cost or slight increases in labour [citation].
artificial neural networks have also been used by many researcher to discriminate weeds with machine vision [citation].
Feasibility analysis showed that the cost of autonomous weeding will be 15% higher than conventional weeding in sugar beet.
Note the high cost of GTS systems as barrier to autonomous system adoption (esp with subscription to RTK and GPS reference signals)

Organic farming scenarios: Operational analysis and costs of implementing innovative technologies

While these technologies increased the capital investment required, the labour demand was reduced by 8385% in sugar beet and 60% in carrots, which would improve profitability by 7285% if fully utilised. Profitability is reduced, if automation efforts result in insufficient weed removal compared to manual weeding. Specifically, the benefit gained by robotic weeding was sensitive to the weed intensity and the initial price of the equipment, but a weeding efficiency of under 25% is required to make it unprofitable
An agricultural mobile robot with vision-based perception for mechanical weed control
motivation for the work reported here is to reduce the amount of herbicides used for crop protection in agriculture by replacing chemical weed control by mechanical weed control
Length of robot is about 120cm and the steering mechanism as an Ackermann steering controllerd with a DC-servo motor.
The robot has two driveing wheels at the rear.
The robot is powered by batteries for indoor testing and by a combustion engine driven generator for field tests.
Agricultural Robotic Platform with Four Wheel Steering for Weed Detection
A modular approach is taken with four identical wheel modules, allowing four wheel steering and propulsion of the platform.
Brushless motor for propulsion with direct drive. All control electronics (motor, amplifier, mcu) are mounted in wheel module.
Wheel module has simple mechanical interface that allows it to be mounted on virtually any vehicle chassis.
Drive system is 12-36V and comms run over a CAN bus.
Autonomous weeders for Christmas tree plantations - a feasibility study
Contains a review of autonomous vehicles in agriculture (and other areas).
Note that skiid steering robots are inappropriate for orchard environements.
Up to now no commercial vehicle platforms, which are easy to adapt for development of an autonomous weeder have been found.
An apparently more suitable vehicle platform has been made by Madsen & Jacobsen (2001) (Figure A.2, appendix A) as their M.Sc. thesis project
No real autonomous machines have yet been marketed for practical purposes, but a few experimental types are being built and offered for sale for research purposes.

The end-effector has an electrode powered by a set of batteries and kills the weeds by producing an electrical discharge of 15 000V.

The robot does not contain a drive system, instead it must be towed behind a tractor. Main componets of the system were the mobile platform, the robotic arm, the manifultaor, the inertial control and the two vision systems.
